\begin_layout Standard
Lift is an elegant, expressive framework that allows any size team build
 and maintain secure, highly interactive, scalable web applications quickly
 and efficiently.
 Lift is built on 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Scala"
target "http://scala-lang.org"

\end_inset

 and compiles to JVM byte-code.
 Lift applications deploy as WAR files on popular application servers and
 web containers including Jetty, Glassfish and Tomcat.
 Lift applications can be monitored and managed with the same proven infrastruct
ure used to manage and monitor any Java web application.
 Lift is open source licensed under an Apache 2.0 license.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Lift features include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Community...
 the Lift community is 2,400 members strong, super-active and always there
 to help with questions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Best Comet (server-push) support that allows the creation of dynamic application
 such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Novell Vibe"
target "http://vibe.novell.com"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Super simple Ajax for creating highly interactive web applications without
 worrying about HTTP plumbing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Secure by default...
 Lift apps are resistant to the OWASP top 10 vulnerabilities including XSS,
 XSRF, and parameter tampering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Concise and Maintainable...
 Lift apps typically contain fewer lines of code than corresponding Rails
 apps, yet are type safe so that many errors are flagged by the compiler
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scalable...
 Lift apps scale to millions of users across many servers, yet are highly
 efficient for single-box implementations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compatible...
 Lift apps can take advantage of any Java library as well as the growing
 collection of Scala libraries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Lift 2.2-RC1 improvements include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
HTML5 Support: Lift supports parsing HTML5 input files and rendering HTML5
 to the browser in addition to Lift's XHTML support
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Wiring"
target "http://demo.liftweb.net/invoice_wiring"

\end_inset

: Spreadsheets meet web application yielding an automatic mechanism for
 updating dependent elements on a page, making it even easier to build dynamic
 apps with Lift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Wizard and Screen Improvements: Build complex screens more easily with new
 helper methods for creating form elements and improved life-cycle callbacks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "CSS Selector Transforms"
target "http://stable.simply.liftweb.net/#sec:CSS-Selector-Transforms"

\end_inset

 Improvements: including appending attributes, multiple selectors applying
 to a single element, and element lifting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Support for migratory sessions: 
\family typewriter
ContainerVars
\family default
 provide type-safe, guaranteed serializable session variables that can migrate
 across application servers in a cluster
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Improved i18n: including per-page localization strings and localization
 strings and HTML stored in templates rather than Java resource files which
 makes editing much easier
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Security Improvements: including creation of new sessions on login
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
MongoDB Improvements: performance improvements as well as new features
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Support for Scala 2.8.1 as well as 2.8.0 and 2.7.7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ProtoUser support for Record: Lift's 
\family typewriter
ProtoUser
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
CRUDify
\family default
 can be used on Record-based persistence classes as well as Mapper-based
 persistence classes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Squeryl integration improvements: Lift is updated to use the latest version
 of Squeryl
\end_layout

